            <h5>
                First and foremost, I would like to thank the team of South Korean ICT volunteers; namely :<br>
Choi Sung-Hyun,
Shin Kiyong,
Lee Sang Chul,
Ko Dong-Woo,
for  making this website finally materialize. Though the project had been started a long time ago, it never took concrete shape for reasons which I will not dwell on at this juncture. I guess it was fated and slated to be left in the hands of this team of young and dynamic Koreans; for good reasons I presume.<br><br>
Young Hearts crossed its Silver Jubilee year in 2015 and this milestone is a source of inspiration and pride for all those associated with this institution. The alumni of this school bear testimony to the efforts of our dedicated faculty that have helped to shape such young minds. Our graduates have carved a niche for themselves not only in Nepal, but the world over by dealing with the challenges of the 21st century head on. Our emphasis on moral and character development, not just academic excellence, have paid dividends and we are always pleased when our ex-students pay us a visit to reflect on their achievements and at the same time give us feedback on what we as an institution should do to cater to meet the needs of the times. Such valuable insight will always be welcome. <br><br>
Finances are a fundamental aspect for the growth of an institution not just in terms of resources, infra structure and facilities but also regular training, workshops ( technical or otherwise ) and seminars for the teachers and students alike. No matter how highly experienced a teacher may be, he or she needs to be upgraded on methodology, child psychology, classroom tools and so forth. Despite financial constraints, we have always tried our best to provide such training and upgrades. Many of our children hail from economically challenging backgrounds and on most occasions are unable to pay even the minimum school fees; however, we do not discriminate, and likewise, we urge our children to see eye to eye on such issues. We try to give the best with the least.<br><br>
A final note before I take leave, I urge the stakeholders ( in this case, students, parents and guardians ) to be  pro-active when it comes to the learning process of their children; moral, academic, social and spiritual so that their children become 'good human beings' and not just a robot with a career.<br><br>
Lift Up Your Hearts<br><br>

